<text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA86">
<l>nīyun tirumakaḷu niṉṟāyāṟ kuṉṟeṭuttup</l>
<l>pāyum paṉimaṟaitta paṇpāḷā – vācaṟ</l>
<l>kaṭaikaḻiyā vuṭpukāk kāmarpūṅ kōva</l>
<l>liṭaikaḻiyē paṟṟi yiṉi</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>You stand there, you and the Lady Śrī, o excellent man who lifted</l>
<l>the mountain and concealed from the spreading water</l>
<l>– without passing by the entrance, without entering inside,</l>
<l>now holding on to the entry hall of Kōval.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the traditional interpretation sees the first reference to the legend of the meeting of the three Āḻvārs in an entry hall of the Tirukkōyilūr temple, that is, the small room where they squeeze all in together when sheltering from the rain where they were then joined by the Lord who inspires them to compose their respective Antāti-s. This verse is quoted, for example, in the mutarāḻvārkaḷ vaipavam of the Kuruparamparāprapāvam (1927, p. 13).</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
